summary: What do you think is significant about Maisie Williams saying that Arya ends the show alone? I I obviously don't think it means...
question: What do you think is significant about Maisie Williams saying that Arya ends the show alone? I I obviously don't think it means that Arya is the only one left, because it being her last scene doesn't mean that it's the last scene of the show, but it is interesting. I'm sad because I'm very much into Gendrya, but I can't really think of a situation that would allow for Gendrya and have Arya in the show alone.
answer:
Dear nonny,

I would like Gendrya as well and there is foreshadowing for it in the books and they played a bit with it on the show as well. As much as I like it I wouldn’t be comfortable with full Gendrya in the books, because Arya is still so young, but I would very much like to have implied future Gendrya.

During the last seasons there is also some foreshadowing that Arya won’t stay in Westeros - the whole what is East of East question - and if Arya has a last scene alone it could mean that she would go on an adventure and leave Westeros at least for a while. Like season 4 ended for her when she left on that ship and looked to the horizon. ‘Bring me to the horizon!’

It would tie in with my idea that Jon and Arya’s reunion - something the readers and the audience wanted for ages - will not be as happy as wished for. GRRM has a tendency to really drive home the lesson of 'Be careful what you wish for, you might get it’ - we all wanted Theon to be punished for his betrayal, but did we want that? We all wanted Cersei to be pulled down but did we want her walk of shame? We all wanted Arya to meet her family again, but did we want her to witness the Red Wedding? I’m convinced that in the books it will be even worse because Arya will meet Lady Stoneheart… Jon expected his sister and will reunite with the 'wrong’ sister in the books… Etc.

So, all this leads me to the conclusion that the Jon/Arya reunion will be very awkward. The show had the very ominous line of Sansa’s : 'His heart will stop when he sees you.’ - Regardless of my predictions the Jon / Arya reunion will be a disappointment for the fans no matter what. They are so super-hyped about it, that there is no way any director could pull it off. Just my two cents obviously.

This would tie in with my idea that Arya will not be too happy about Jonsa. I think it will take her some time to accept it and leaving Westeros for a time might be what she thinks is best and what will fit to her adventurous and curious nature. It would also give a little piece of sadness to the ending. The knowledge that some things changed and can never be again as they were.

That does not necessarily exclude Gendrya. I would be very happy if we get something along the lines of : 'when I return I’ll visit you at your smithy.’ or even something like 'I guess I’ll wait for you my lady.’ We could get heavily implied post-canon Gendrya, and I would really like all the post-canon fics we would get from that. It also would be a scenario I can imagine in the books as well. Say Arya is fifteen by the time of ADOS, she leaves for five years and becomes Gendry’s wife after that and visits Jon and Sansa and is the most beloved aunt that tells all kind of cool stories. I could certainly live with that! Bonus if we get an epilogue with Jon and Sansa and their kids and the impending visit of aunt Arya and uncle Gendry is mentioned. That would make me cry for joy!

So, I don’t think you should despair yet. Actually in the books I think implied post-canon Gendrya is the most likely scenario.

Thanks for the ask!
